{[show S]South opens a strong notrump, and responder must choose between signing off in game and probing for slam.
[BID 1N] ⟦You have 15 to 17 balanced, so open 1NT and let partner judge the level.⟧ Your partner bids 4\H, a Texas transfer to spades — it shows a six-card spade suit and asks opener to complete. This is a close call: with a maximum opposite, partner could instead start a Jacoby 2\D and explore quantitatively, since the combined values brush the slam zone. Signing off through Texas is sound, but a slam try is defensible.
[BID 4S] ⟦You complete the transfer with 4\S as Texas requires, placing the partnership in the spade game.⟧
[show NS]South held \S65 \HAJ3 \DAKT76 \CA75, a chunky 16. North's Texas 4\H named the six-card spade suit and chose to play game; with 29 or 30 combined, a Jacoby route inviting slam would also have been reasonable. The lesson: Texas is the right tool to sign off, but judge whether the hands are too good to stop in game.}
[Note "1:Texas"]
