{[show S]South opens a strong notrump; responder transfers to the major, then explores slam with Roman Key Card Blackwood.
[BID 1N] ⟦You have 15 to 17 balanced, so open 1NT and let partner steer.⟧ Your partner bids 4\H, a Texas transfer to spades showing a six-card suit. Choosing Texas now, rather than Jacoby, sets up a 4NT follow that asks for keycards with no shortness to show.
[BID 4S] ⟦You complete the transfer with 4\S, naming the agreed major as Texas requires.⟧ Your partner bids 4NT, Roman Key Card Blackwood agreeing spades and asking for the five keycards — the four aces plus the king of trumps. Under 1430 the steps are: 5\C = one or four, 5\D = zero or three, 5\H = two without the trump queen, 5\S = two with it.
[BID 5H] ⟦You answer 5\H, showing two keycards without the trump queen.⟧ With a keycard missing, your partner signs off in 5\S, stopping safely below a slam that cannot be guaranteed.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 5\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]South held \S98 \HAKJ3 \DQJ83 \CAQ5, a 17-count. North transferred with Texas, then 4NT asked for keycards; South's 5\H showed two, and with one keycard missing the partnership rested in 5\S. The lesson: Texas first, then 4NT, lets the partnership try for slam and pull up short of it when a keycard is absent.}
[Note "1:Texas"]
[Note "2:Blackwood 1430, for !S"]
[Note "3:A=2/5 or 5/5, Q(S)=0"]
