{[show S]South opens 1NT, and responder must judge whether to push for slam after Texas. This one is genuinely close — the keycard count invites a slam that needs friendly cards to make.
[BID 1N] ⟦You have a balanced 15 to 17, so open 1NT and let partner weigh the slam.⟧ 4\H is a Texas Transfer to spades, showing a six-card spade suit with game values and slam interest held back, asking opener to bid 4\S.
[BID 4S] ⟦You complete the transfer by bidding 4\S, the suit partner showed.⟧ Here is the close call: Your partner tries for slam with 4NT, Roman Key Card Blackwood agreeing spades and asking for the five keycards — the four aces plus the king of trumps. Under 1430 the steps are: 5\C = one or four, 5\D = zero or three, 5\H = two without the trump queen, 5\S = two with it. Signing off in 4\S is equally defensible — the values are there but the slam needs the cards to lie well, so a player who passes 4\S over the completion has not erred.
[BID 5S] ⟦You answer 5\S, the top step of the ladder, showing two keycards.⟧ Reading enough between the hands, your partner pushes on to 6\S — the aggressive choice, accepting the slam.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 6\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]South opened 1NT with \SJT94 \HAQ7 \DAKQ \CJ62 — a balanced 17 — and completed the Texas transfer to 4\S. Whether to push past game was a true judgment call: the keycards point at slam, but 6\S needs the suits to break, and resting in 4\S would have been the safer road. Texas gives responder room to ask either way.}
